      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The leak in your code is due to the fact that you're not deleting the `DataBuffer` object after you're done with it. In C++, when you create an object on the heap using `new`, you're responsible for deleting it when you're done with it to avoid memory leaks.\n\nHowever, in your case, you're using a smart pointer (`DataBuffer*`) to manage the object, so you might think that the compiler will automatically delete it for you. But, in this case, the `DataBuffer` class doesn't implement the `std::destructor` operator, so the object is not being deleted when it goes out of scope.\n\nTo fix the leak, you need to delete the `DataBuffer` object manually after you're done with it. You can do this by using a `std::unique_ptr` instead of a raw pointer, which will automatically delete the object when it goes out of scope.\n\nHere's an updated version of your code:\n\n```cpp\n#include <iostream>\n#include <memory>\n\nclass DataBuffer {\npublic:\n    DataBuffer(int size) : size(size) {\n        data = new char[size];\n        std::cout << \"Buffer allocated\" << std::endl;\n    }",
